rduous and expensive adoption process only to leave them unable to fully function under the law as a family.\r\n\r\nWhen all was said and done, the professor withdrew his application though he was one of the top candidates for the position. As any good father would, he put his family first. The college was frustrated and disappointed that its top candidate withdrew because of the inequities of Minnesota laws, and the state lost a potential new citizen.\r\n\r\nMinnesotans believe in fairness and equality, but unless our state laws reflect the equality we value, Minnesota will continue to lose new residents and families that could benefit Minnesota businesses, schools and communities.','A Missed Opportunity for the State','','inherit','open','open','','229-revision-3','','','2011-03-27 01:43:51','2011-03-27 06:43:51','',229,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/229-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(292,4,'2011-03-27 03:05:09','2011-03-27 08:05:09','Project 515 will be at the 16th Annual Rainbow Families Conference on April 9 at Anwatin/Bryn Mawr Schools in Minneapolis.\n\nCome check us out! And check out the \"premier community building event for LGBT parents and their children, prospective parents, family members, friends, educators and community members.\"\n\nThis year\'s theme is “Ending Bullying in our Community” and will feature Jamie Nabozny from the documentary “Bullied.”\n\nRainbow Families Conference, April 9, 2011\n\nContact Mel Rexroad, Midwest Region Senior Manager for Rainbow Families, with any questions about the conference or call 651.644.4848 x1','Visit Project 515 at the 16th Annual Rainbow Families Conference on April 9','','inherit','open','open','','288-revision','','','2011-03-27 03:05:09','2011-03-27 08:05:09','',288,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/288-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(293,4,'2011-03-27 03:05:55','2011-03-27 08:05:55','Project 515 will be at the 16th Annual Rainbow Families Conference on April 9 at Anwatin/Bryn Mawr Schools in Minneapolis.\r\n\r\nCo