ve continued. \"As a parent of a lesbian daughter, I want what I expect for all three of my children: equality and fairness, whether they’re gay, lesbian or straight.\"','It’s Not About Benefits, But Acceptance','','inherit','open','open','','241-revision-3','','','2011-03-27 03:18:18','2011-03-27 08:18:18','',241,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/241-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(318,8,'2011-03-27 03:19:57','2011-03-27 08:19:57','Multi-ethnic couple hugging','81388081_47','','inherit','open','open','','81388081_47','','','2011-03-27 03:19:57','2011-03-27 08:19:57','',243,'http://fcw.lan/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/81388081_47.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(319,8,'2011-03-27 02:00:57','2011-03-27 07:00:57','Shannon was pregnant with twins and fell so ill that she could no longer work. She was unable to qualify for insurance on her partner’s insurance plan, so she applied for medical assistance, which was available only because she was pregnant. After the twins were born and her health returned, the couple more closely examined the domestic-partner benefits available through the employer of Shannon’s partner.\r\n\r\nBenefits were available to Shannon and to the children, but the costs were extremely high. Not only would the amount paid for Shannon’s coverage be taxable, but the employer’s contribution would have been taxable as well. In addition, the plan considered the children Shannon’s, so taxes would have been withheld on contributions for their insurance coverage, too. The combination of costs made it impossible for Shannon and her partner to afford.\r\n\r\nTheir only recourse would have been for Shannon’s partner to file an affidavit at the end of each year to prove the children were legally hers. Even then, they would not have received the tax money reimbursement until they filed their taxes the following year.\r\n\r\nThe solution?\r\n\r\n\"Only the children are covered,\" Shannon said. \"If I am not on the plan, they consider the children to be legally hers, as the employee. No proof required. If we were married, no one would question if the children were legally my partner’s.\"\r\n','Navigating the Inequality of Insurance Law','','inherit','open','open','','243-revision-2','','','2011-03-27 02:00:57','2011-03-27 07:00:57','',243,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/243-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(320,4,'2011-03-27 03:23:51','2011-03-27 08:23:51','<a title=\"Link to video\" href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2yRYFMlDzE&amp;feature=channel_video_title\" target=\"_blank\">Ann Kaner-Roth on Comcast Newsmakers</a>\nWednesday, February 16, 2011 at 2:35 PM\n\nReligious beliefs at root of Catch-22 for same-sex couples\nMonday, June 07, 2010 at 11:15 AM\n\nEditorial: \'Final Wishes\' veto is cold, calculating\nMonday, May 24, 2010 at 6:45 PM\n\nPawlenty vows veto of same-sex measure; Extending \'end-of-life\' rights at issue\nThursday, May 13, 2010 at 12:15 PM\n\nTim Pawlenty and the Rights of Dying Gay People\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 3:35 PM\n\nSenator urges Pawlenty to sign ‘final wishes’ bill\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 3:10 PM\n\nPawlenty says he\'ll veto same-sex couples bill\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 1:50 PM\n\nLegislature passes ‘death rights’ bill for same-sex couples, Pawlenty threatens veto\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 12:25 PM\n\nEnd-of-Life Bill Headed to Minn. Gov.\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 11:50 AM\n\nHouse passes bill that gives gay couples the right to make end-of-life decisions, Pawlenty\'s position on bill unknown\nWednesday, May 12, 2010 at 11:00 AM\n\nHouse passes bill to give same-sex couples some rights\nTuesday, May 11, 2010 at 11:35 AM\n\nRepair Laws that discriminate against same-sex couples\nWednesday, April 21, 2010 at 10:20 AM\n\nReader\'s view: Bill a common sense measure that erases discrimination\nSaturday, April 10, 2010 at 1:10 PM\nLetter to the Editor: Final Wishes/Wrongful Death bill is fair\nTuesday, April 06, 2010 at 11:10 AM\n\nSame-sex couples glad to be counted in U.S. census\nTuesd