e Out to the Ballgame.\" I have no fear that a bureaucrat or death panel would override my partner.\r\n\r\nThat\'s because we have this magic document that makes it all work. It\'s called a marriage license.\r\n\r\nI am preambling my way toward Senate File 341, vetoed by Gov. Tim Pawlenty during the hectic last weekend of the Legislative session three weeks ago. It was the latest battle in a long conflict I call Love versus Government. The vetoed bill would have extended rights regarding after-death disposition of remains and rights-to-sue to couples who are no less committed than my partner and I but who cannot have the magic document because they are boy-boy or girl-girl and not, as we happen to be, boy-girl.\r\n\r\nIn a 1998 gubernatorial debate over same-sex rights, while the two big-party candidates recited their well-scripted positions, candidate Jesse Ventura told a story about two same-gender friends, together for four decades, who feared that they have no bedside, end-of-life rights. \"I don\'t believe government should be so hostile, so mean spirited,\" he said. \"Love is bigger than government.\"\r\n\r\nI took Ventura to mean not that government should approve his friends\' relationship but that it had no business in this intimate, personal, private area of our lives. Two years later, then-Gov. Ventura proposed extending health-care benefits to the same-sex partners of state employees. Not marriage, mind you — just coverage. Those benefits stirred a huge political fight and existed in union contracts for a brief interlude, according to a state union official.\r\n\r\nIt is now a decade after Ventura\'s modest proposal, and the bill Pawlenty vetoed was yet another attempt to extend certain rights to \"unlicensed\" couples. Nearly all of these efforts have died due to steadfast opposition from Republicans, the party of \"personal freedom\" and \"limited government,\" who controlled the House during Ventura\'s tenure and, since 2003, the governorship.\r\n\r\nMarriage has long been defined in Minnesota law as a civil contract between a man and a woman. In the mid-1990s, when state courts elsewhere began ruling that denying the license to same-sex couples was unconstitutional, the U.S. government and the state added \"defense of marriage\" statutes. The Minnesota law specifically prohibits \"marriage between persons of the same sex.\"\r\n\r\nFive states and Washington D.C. allow same-sex marriage. Five others allow non-religious \"civil unions\" or \"domestic partnerships\" that extend the rights of married couples to same-sex unions, and several others extend limited rights to same-sex partners. In all those states, religions are free to marry, and to refuse to marry, as they see fit.\r\n\r\nMarriage has deep meaning and importance to society, and to me personally. Marriage and family were my goals in life but I didn\'t fully realize this until I attained them. Being called \"husband\" and \"dad\" is a thrill and a tribute I try to live up to. I do not see family love as a zero-sum game, in which some other household\'s happiness subtracts from my quota.\r\n\r\nThose without the license are in limbo. They can set up households, jointly own property, adopt children or even, with help from a third party, produce their own biological offspring. They have no social, legal or cultural recognition of their bond. Quite the opposite — if they are of the same sex, they confront the drumbeat of religious teaching that their love is wrong, sinful and evil.\r\n\r\nSenate File 341 deals with rights that government confers on those holding the marriage license when the partner dies: the right to make decisions on a loved one\'s remains and the right to sue for a partner\'s wrongful death. The bill would extend those rights to the deceased person\'s \"domestic partner.\"\r\n\r\nIf these couples cannot marry but are to be given these rights, there must be a legal definition of what their relationship is. Those who want to withhold the license also oppose any such definition as a threat to those of us with the license. They also say such definitions are vague or \"subjective,\" which is true — because the word \"marriage\" cannot be used.\r\n\r\nIt\'s a political Catch-22 that works like a charm.\r\n\r\n\"Domestic partners\" were defined in this doomed bill as same-sex couples (meaning, those who do not have the option to marry) who have \"assumed responsibility for each other\'s basic common welfare, financial obligations and well-being,\" who \"share a common domicile ... on a permanent basis,\" and who \"have a committed interdependent relationship, intend to continue it, and do not have this type of relationship with another person.\"\r\n\r\nPawlenty said in his veto letter that this definition depends upon \"subjective criteria.\" (Catch-22!) He said \"a \'domestic partner\' would be afforded the same legal recognition for purposes of the wrongful death laws as a spouse.\' \" (Uh, that\'s the point.) He added: \"Marriage — defined as between a man and a woman — should remain elevated in our society at a special level, as it traditionally has been.\"\r\n\r\nBut as Pawlenty jettisoned the bill, he said (twice) that any person can designate someone to dispose of his or her remains \"by executing a will.\" I take that as an admission that same-sex couples do have a right to designate each other in the same way that my licensed partner and I have. I call that a small victory for Love.\r\n\r\nThis public fight is entangled in the roots of religious belief. I think of the spreading, underground structure of the giant silver maple in our backyard, which holds up a beautiful tree but also buckles our driveway and tilts our privacy fence.\r\n\r\nThe religious roots of this debate are subterranean but powerful. Can we complain about the roots even as we enjoy the tree they sustain? Perhaps, but those of us who harp on the influence of the \"religious right\" could spare a little love for good and decent people who cannot believe otherwise than that \"marriage\" is meant for one man and one woman.\r\n\r\nRep. Paul Kohls, R-Victoria, spoke against the bill when it came before the House. I called him and asked why. \"We\'re trying to get to someplace that I just don\'t think we can go,\" he said. \"We have throughout the ages, we have a bias in favor of heterosexual marriage,\" he said. \"I happen to think that is not inappropriate.\"\r\n\r\nThe obvious compromise, which many people of good will can accept, is for government to confer equal rights and benefits and for churches to proceed according to their own rules. But even that modest step, embodied in Senate File 341, is entangled in those powerful roots and is shot down by Catch-22 politics.\r\n\r\nThis is not George Orwell and \"1984,\" where human love was forbidden by the all-seeing government. But doesn\'t it at least lean in that direction? So far in Minnesota, to twist Ventura\'s phrase, government has proven to be bigger than love, even after we breathe our last.\r\n\r\n<em>Jim Ragsdale is a Pioneer Press editorial writer and columnist. His e-mail address is jragsdale@pioneerpress.com. The original article was posted on the Pioneer Press website.</em>','Religious beliefs at root of Catch-22 for same-sex couples','','publish','open','open','','religious-beliefs-at-root-of-catch-22-for-same-sex-couples','','','2011-03-27 03:31:07','2011-03-27 08:31:07','',0,'http://fcw.lan/?p=342',0,'post','',0),(343,8,'2011-03-27 03:29:15','2011-03-27 08:29:15','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://fcw.lan/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/iStock_000013316307Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-337\" title=\"iStock_000013316307Small\" src=\"http://fcw.lan/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/iStock_000013316307Small.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"543\" height=\"433\" /></a></p>\r\nDallas Drake was a trusted and familiar face in his community after dedicating his career to protecting his neighbors. He was the first openly gay firefighter in Minnesota. But when he tried to retrieve his car from the impound lot after the death of his long-time partner Joe Shulka, the clerk at the suburban Twin Cities impound lot said, “the police department told me not to release it to you because you’re not the next of kin.”\r\n\r\nDallas and Joe began their partnership in 1991 after meeting at a local event. Through the years they bought a house, started a non-profit organization and enjoyed the thrill of chasing a Minnesota summer storm. They understood that Minnesota laws did not recognize their same-sex relationship, so they made sure to list each other as the power of attorney and executor in their wills.\r\n\r\nJoe took his own life in September 2008. He could no longer take the daily insults hurled at him about his sexuality and the discrimination he faced as a gay man. In the early 1990s he was nearly beaten to death by a group of men who suspected he was gay. These pressures, along with recent financial trouble, were too much for Joe to bear. He ended his life in a local hotel room.\r\n\r\nDallas waited more than a day-and-a-half for any word about Joe’s whereabouts. Finally, Joe’s sister called to say Joe was gone. The medical examiner refused to call Dallas directly even though instructions for who should be notified were in Joe’s wallet. When Dallas tried to withdraw money from Joe’s bank account, he was denied access. Six weeks after Joe’s death, armed with a death certificate and the help of a judge’s order, Dallas finally accessed his account to pay his bills. Dallas had no recourse with financial institutions, insurance companies and other companies even though both Dallas and Joe were both listed on the accounts.\r\n\r\n“The most difficult part is that I lost half of me the day Joe died,” Dallas said. “But I also lost my income, my companionship and understanding. I can’t do this without my partner.”\r\n\r\n“The fact is, if our relationship was legally recognized I would not have had to wait so long. No one would have questioned my access to my bank account, my car or Joe’s social security or paycheck,” he said.\r\n\r\nDallas and Joe spent their lives working to solve unnecessary death through their work at the Center for Homicide Research. Ironically, the journey of Dallas and Joe was interrupted by death. They participated fully in the collective human story, but their relationship wasn’t recognized in life or in death.','Unrecognized in life and death','','inherit','open','open','','251-revision-3','','','2011-03-27 03:29:15','2011-03-27 08:29:15','',251,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/251-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(344,8,'2011-03-27 03:30:35','2011-03-27 08:30:35','Holding hands','87325192_47','','inherit','open','open','','87325192_47','','','2011-03-27 03:30:35','2011-03-27 08:30:35','',253,'http://fcw.lan/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/87325192_47.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(345,8,'2011-03-27 02:07:08','2011-03-27 07:07:08','Randy and Tom’s relationship was like many others — camping trips, vacations to Tom’s family farm in Illinois and helping raise Randy’s two kids. “It was not nirvana, it was not perfect — no relationship is — but it was a real relationship,” Randy said.\r\n\r\nSix years into their life together, Tom began having difficulty swallowing. Following a Northern Minnesota camping trip in late July 2006, Tom’s doctor diagnosed him with esophageal cancer and admitted him to the hospital.\r\n\r\nThe following days and months were challenging — breaking the news to Randy’s kids and their families; chemotherapy and radiation treatments; late night trips to urgent care to treat the horrible side effects; a feeding tube; and a December 22 surgery to remove and replace Tom’s esophagus.\r\n\r\n“He was bound and determined it wasn’t going to beat him,” Randy said. After the surgery, “we thought we were on the road to recovery.” Still, Randy and Tom made sure their house was in order. They reviewed their powers of attorney, wills and other available legal documents.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, Tom had a major setback and underwent a Christmas morning emergency surgery. The next five months saw a series of ups and downs. Then in late April, the cancer returned with a vengeance. Tom died May 4, 2007.\r\n\r\nThrough it all, Randy spent hours at the hospital every day, making the life and death decisions and keeping their families and friends informed while working full time and being there for his children. “I was the caregiver and rightfully so,” Randy said “That’s just what you do when you love someone.”\r\n\r\nThe next painful step was to make funeral arrangements and it was at this point that Minnesota’s discriminatory policies became abundantly clear. On the morning of Tom’s death, the Cremation Society notified Randy he would need one of Tom’s legal next of kin to sign the release for Tom’s body and make funeral arrangements because Minnesota law didn’t recognize their relationship. The Cremation Society employee, gracious but resolute, told Randy his power of attorney ended when Tom died.\r\n\r\n“All of a sudden you’re an outsider,” Randy said. “For hours each and every day for five months, I was there as Tom’s partner. Yet I’m not allowed to take on the final responsibility and carry out Tom’s wishes. We need to turn that around.”\r\n','When a power of attorney doesn’t work any longer','','inherit','open','open','','253-revision-2','','','2011-03-27 02:07:08','2011-03-27 07:07:08','',253,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/253-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(346,4,'2011-03-27 03:29:55','2011-03-27 08:29:55','','Religious beliefs at root of Catch-22 for same-sex couples','','inherit','open','open','','342-revision','','','2011-03-27 03:29:55','2011-03-27 08:29:55','',342,'http://fcw.lan/2011/03/27/342-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(347,8,'2011-03-27 03:31:49','2011-03-27 08:31:49','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://fcw.lan/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/87325192_47.jpg\"><img class=\